products.description: This work is part of a series around the Western myth of the Valkyries, a metaphor for a woman with a conscious illustrated in what she does with her arms. Women in art are often depicted as female bodies. I chose to only show her back for its non-threatening feel. The woman holds the spear which embodies her intellect, strength and dangerousness. 105cm x 74cm, White crayon, black paper. Original title: .  About the artist: Tsai Wan-jin () is a surrealist artist, graduate from New York Long Island University in Creative Arts and currently PhD student at National Taiwan University. products.description:
This work is part of a series around the Western myth of the Valkyries, a metaphor for a woman with a conscious illustrated in what she does with her arms. The woman holds an ax and evokes Athena, the goddess of war in Greek mythology. Here the ax represents wisdom and courage while the fur neck represents wealth, power and femininity. Her hand is on her chest to represent her sensitivity as a woman. Her half-naked body displays the innate qualities of the female body.
58cm x 72cm, White crayon, black paper. Original title: .  About the artist: Tsai Wan-jin () is a surrealist artist, graduate from New York Long Island University in Creative Arts and currently PhD student at National Taiwan University. Her first solo exhibition took place in New York in 2008.

products.description: For Ligne Roset, Ruch brings together the unusual and the traditional. The name refers to a sewing technique in which fabric is gathered or pleated; it has long served as a decoration for clothing. The unusual thing about this piece is its solid wood structure, and the traditional element: the quilting, the very heart of Ligne Roset's savoir-faire. Its tall uprights and the undulations of its duvet combine to produce a harmonious union of rigorous straight lines and soft, welcoming curves. Slender and fine, Ruch is nonetheless soft and welcoming.
products.title: Ruch
